== Municipalities in the province of Belluno == One ''[[comune]]'' (municipality) in the [[Province of Belluno]], [[Sappada]], was historically part of Friuli. In 2010, the ''comune'' formally asked to become part of Friuli-Venezia Giulia and the Regional Council of Friuli-Venezia Giulia accepted the municipality's demand. Other ''comuni'' in the Province of Belluno are listed in the [[#Friulian place names outside of Friuli|Friulian place names outside of Friuli]] section below. {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Italian (map form) !! Standard Friulian !! Other forms / Notes |- | ''[[Sappada]]'' || ''Sapàde''{{listref|D}} || ''Plodarsich'' [[Bavarian language|Bavarian]]: ''Plodn'';{{listref|C}} [[German Language|German]]: ''Pladen''{{listref|C}} |}
== Municipalities in the Metropolitan City of Venice == Several ''[[comune|comuni]]'' (municipalities) in the eastern part of the [[Metropolitan City of Venice]] (formerly the [[Province of Venice]]) between the rivers [[Livenza]] and [[Tagliamento]] in the region known as the {{illm|Mandamento of Portogruaro|it|Mandamento di Portogruaro|fur|Mandament di Puart}} were historically part of Friuli. The Friulian names of these ''comuni'' are listed here. Other ''comuni'' in the Province of Venice are listed in the [[#Friulian place names outside of Friuli|Friulian place names outside of Friuli]] section below. It is estimated that 29% of the population in these areas speaks fluent [[Friuli]]. The language is officially recognized and has been protected as a minority language since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politichesociali.provincia.venezia.it/upload/servizi/00000001/00000021/2006_00120.pdf|title=Provincia di Venezia|publisher=Politichesociali.provincia.venezia.it|accessdate=5 August 2015|language=Italian}} {{it icon}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Italian (map form) !! Standard Friulian !! Other forms / Notes |- | ''[[Annone Veneto]]'' || ''Danòn''{{listref|D}} || Local [[Venetian language|Venetian]] (''Liventino''): ''Danón'';<ref>Giovanna Ruzzene. ''Jèra 'na volta Danón.'' Annone Veneto: Editrice per Annone, 2006. {{it icon}}</ref> Venetian: ''Anon'' |- | ''[[Caorle]]'' || ''Cjàurlis''{{listref|D}} || Alternative Friulian: ''Cjàorle'';{{listref|C}} Venetian: ''Càorle'' |- | [[Cinto Caomaggiore]] || Cint{{listref|D}} || Alternative Friulian: ''Cinto'';{{listref|C}} Venetian: ''Sinto Caomagior'' |- | ''[[Concordia Sagittaria]]'' || ''Cuncuàrdie''{{listref|D}} || Alternative Friulian: ''Concuàrdie'';{{listref|C}} Venetian: ''Concordia'' |- | ''[[Fossalta di Portogruaro]]'' || ''Fossàlte''{{listref|D}} || Venetian: ''Fosalta de Portogruaro'' |- | ''[[Gruaro]]'' || ''Gruâr''{{listref|D}} || Venetian: ''Gruèr'', ''Gruàr'' |- | ''[[Portogruaro]]'' || ''Puàrt di Gruâr''{{listref|D}} || Alternative Friulian: ''Puàrt'',{{listref|C}} ''Puàrt Gruâr'';{{listref|C}} Local Venetian: ''Portogruèr'';<ref>Sanudo Marin. ''[http://lamalcontenta.com/publications/La%20Malcontenta%20Editions/2004%20Vitae%20dei%20Dogi%20di%20Marin%20Sanudo%20(1423-74)%20-%20Vol.%202.pdf Le vite dei dogi 1423-1474]''. La Malcontenta. {{it icon}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312195942/http://lamalcontenta.com/publications/La%20Malcontenta%20Editions/2004%20Vitae%20dei%20Dogi%20di%20Marin%20Sanudo%20%281423-74%29%20-%20Vol.%202.pdf |date=March 12, 2013 }}</ref> Venetian: ''Pòrto'';<ref>''Dizionario di toponomastica. Storia e significato dei nomi geografici italiani''. Turin: UTET, 2006. p. 605. {{it icon}}</ref> German: ''Portogruar''{{listref|C}} |- | ''[[Pramaggiore]]'' || ''Pramaiôr''{{listref|D}} || Venetian: ''Pramagiòr'', ''Pramajor'' |- | [[San Michele al Tagliamento]] || San Michêl{{listref|D}} || Alternative Friulian: ''San Micjêl'';{{listref|C}} Venetian: ''San Michièl al Tajamento'' |- | ''[[San Stino di Livenza]]'' || ''San Stin''{{listref|D}} || Italian until 2011: ''Santo Stino di Livenza''; Venetian: ''San Stin dea Livensa'' |- | [[Teglio Veneto]] || Tei{{listref|D}} || Venetian: ''Tejo Vèneto'' |}
