{{History of Burma}}
[[Image:Burma indo china 1886.jpg|thumb|left|Lower Burma in pink, as opposed to [[Upper Burma]] in orange.]]

'''Lower Burma''' ({{lang-my|အောက်မြန်မာပြည်}}, also called '''Outer Myanmar''') is a geographic region of [[Burma]] (Myanmar) and includes the low-lying [[Irrawaddy delta]] ([[Ayeyarwady Region|Ayeyarwady]], [[Bago Region|Bago]] and [[Yangon Region]]s), as well as coastal regions of the country ([[Rakhine State|Rakhine]] and [[Mon State]]s and [[Tanintharyi Region]]).

In the [[Burmese language]], people originating from [[Upper Burma]] are typically called ''a-htet-tha'' for men and ''a-hiet-lhu'' for women, whereas those from Lower Burma are called ''auk tha'' ({{my|အောက်သား}}) for men and ''auk thu'' for women.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gustaaf Houtman|title=Traditions of Buddhist Practice in Burma|year=1990|publisher=ILCAA|isbn=|page=266}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=October 2018}} While ''a-nya tha'' ({{my|အညာသား}}) refers to interior inhabitants of the country.<ref>{{cite book|author=W. H. Sloan|title=A Practical Method with the Burmese Language|year=1876|publisher=American Mission Press|isbn=|page=74}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=October 2018}}

Historically, Lower Burma referred to the part of [[Burma]] annexed by the [[British Empire]] after the end of the [[Second Burmese War|Second Anglo-Burmese War]] in 1852,<ref>{{cite book|author=Mya Than|title=Myanmar's External Trade: An Overview in the Southeast Asian Context|year=1992|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian|isbn=98-130-1613-2|page=7}}</ref> plus the former kingdom of [[Rakhine State|Arakan]] and the territory of [[Tanintharyi Region|Tenasserim]] which the British had taken control of in 1826 through the [[Treaty of Yandabo]].<ref>{{cite book|author=James Stuart Olson & Robert Shadle|title=Historical Dictionary of the British Empire, Volume 1|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=03-132-9366-X|page=214}}</ref> Lower Burma was centred at [[Rangoon]], and composed of all of the coast of modern [[Burma]], and also the lower basin of the [[Ayeyarwady River|Irrawaddy River]], including [[Prome]]. Until the early 19th century, Lower Burma was predominantly populated by the [[Mon people|Mon]] and [[Karen people|Karen]] tribes and was a historical stronghold of the Mon people.

