[[File:West Florida Map 1767.jpg|thumb|[[British West Florida]] and [[British East Florida]] (pink) from a 1767 map. [[Southern Florida|Southern East Florida]] is not shown.]] [[File:West Florida Map.png|thumb|The Baton Rouge and Mobile Districts of [[Spanish West Florida]] (red), claimed by the United States, spanned parts of three later states. The Spanish province also included part of the present state of Florida.]] [[File:1822 Geographical, Statistical, and Historical Map of Florida by Henry Charles Carey, Isaac Lea and Fielding Lucas.png|thumb|right|225px|Under Spanish rule, Florida was divided by the natural separation of the [[Suwannee River]] into West Florida and East Florida. (map: [[Henry Charles Carey|Carey]] & [[Isaac Lea|Lea]], 1822)]] '''The Floridas''' was a region of the southeastern United States comprising the historical colonies of [[East Florida]] and [[West Florida]]. The borders of East and West Florida varied. In 1783, when Spain acquired West Florida and re-acquired East Florida from Great Britain through the [[Peace of Paris (1783)]], the eastern British boundary of West Florida was the Apalachicola River, but Spain in 1785 moved it eastward to the [[Suwannee River]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wright|first=J. Leitch|date=1972|title=Research Opportunities in the Spanish Borderlands: West Florida, 1781–1821|work= Latin American Research Review|volume= 7|number=2|publisher= Latin American Studies Association|pages=24–34|jstor= 2502623}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Spanish Frontier in North America|first=David J. |last=Weber| url=https://books.google.com/?id=KOPdX2qaVrkC&pg=PA458&lpg=PA458&dq=%22West+Florida%22+Spain+Apalachee+1785+%22San+Marcos%22#v=onepage&q=%22West%20Florida%22%20Spain%20Apalachee%201785%20%22San%20Marcos%22&f=false |location=New Haven, Connecticut, USA |year=1992 |publisher=Yale University Press|page=275|isbn=978-0-300-05917-5|quote=Spain never drew a clear line to separate the two Floridas, but West Florida extended easterly to include Apalachee Bay, which Spain shifted from the jurisdiction of St. Augustine to more accessible Pensacola.}}</ref> The purpose was to transfer San Marcos and the district of Apalachee from East Florida to West Florida.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jud10.flcourts.org/?q=content/history-florida-maps|title=The Evolution of a State, Map of Florida Counties – 1820| publisher=10th Circuit Court of Florida|accessdate=2016-01-26|quote=Under Spanish rule, Florida was divided by the natural separation of the Suwanee River into West Florida and East Florida.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedestinlog.com/article/20150904/NEWS/150909574|title=History Mystery: Was Destin Once in Walton County?|first=Hank|last=Klein| publisher=The Destin Log|accessdate=2016-01-26|quote=On July 21, 1821 all of what had been West Florida was named Escambia County, after the Escambia River. It stretched from the Perdido River to the Suwanee River with its county seat at Pensacola.}}</ref> From 1810 to 1813, the United States extended piecemeal control over the part of West Florida that comprised the modern-day [[Gulf of Mexico|Gulf]] coasts of [[Alabama]] and [[Mississippi]] and the [[Florida Parishes]] of [[Louisiana]]. After the ratification of the [[Adams-Onis Treaty]] in 1821 the United States combined East Florida and what had been the remaining Spanish-controlled rump of West Florida into the territory that comprised modern-day Florida.
